    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2329421888" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2329421888" />
    <a title="Emma Deplores Goodreads Censorship" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5229326-emma-deplores-goodreads-censorship"><img alt="Emma Deplores Goodreads Censorship" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1325201543p2/5229326.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2329421888?book_show_action=true">Jul 03, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Emma Deplores Goodreads Censorship" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Emma Deplores Goodreads Censorship" href="/user/show/5229326-emma-deplores-goodreads-censorship">Emma Deplores Goodreads Censorship</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780618074518" href="/book/show/35997.Clear_Light_of_Day">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5229326-emma-deplores-goodreads-censorship?shelf=india">india</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5229326-emma-deplores-goodreads-censorship?shelf=4-stars">4-stars</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5229326-emma-deplores-goodreads-censorship?shelf=best-10-books-read-in-2019">best-10-books-read-in-2019</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5229326-emma-deplores-goodreads-censorship?shelf=literary-fiction">literary-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2329421888" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3347530157695363747">I liked this book a lot. It’s an emotionally rich and nuanced tale of four adult siblings and their formative years in an old home in Delhi, where the tough, passionate older sister, Bimla, still lives, teaching history and caring for their mentally challenged younger brother. The timid younger sister, Tara, now married to a diplomat, returns for a visit, and tries to bridge the gap between Bim and their absent older brother, with whom she’s had a falling-out. It’s not a fast-paced story, but it</span>
  <span id="freeText3347530157695363747" style="display:none">I liked this book a lot. It’s an emotionally rich and nuanced tale of four adult siblings and their formative years in an old home in Delhi, where the tough, passionate older sister, Bimla, still lives, teaching history and caring for their mentally challenged younger brother. The timid younger sister, Tara, now married to a diplomat, returns for a visit, and tries to bridge the gap between Bim and their absent older brother, with whom she’s had a falling-out. It’s not a fast-paced story, but it is a well-written, layered, and meaningful one, taking a close look at its complex, sympathetic characters and the nuances of their interactions and memories. It reminded me of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2154433.Evening_Is_the_Whole_Day" title="Evening Is the Whole Day by Preeta Samarasan" rel="nofollow noopener">Evening Is the Whole Day</a>, which I also loved, though that book is almost lurid by comparison. I would definitely recommend this to those who enjoy insightful family stories, and who enjoy books driven more by strong characters and writing than by plot.<br /><br />A couple of notes: the book isn’t as short as the page count would make it seem (there’s a lot of words on a page), and the cover seems off-base, considering how often the siblings’ skin is referred to as “white.” Even granting that probably means something different in India than the U.S., I can’t help thinking there’s some exoticizing going on with that choice of image.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3347530157695363747" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


