<div id="review_352976164" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/352976164" />
    <a title="Chaitra" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9086236-chaitra"><img alt="Chaitra" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1432611617p2/9086236.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/352976164?book_show_action=true">Jun 21, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chaitra" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chaitra" href="/user/show/9086236-chaitra">Chaitra</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780618074518" href="/book/show/35997.Clear_Light_of_Day">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9086236-chaitra?shelf=booker-prize-nominees">booker-prize-nominees</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9086236-chaitra?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9086236-chaitra?shelf=family">family</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9086236-chaitra?shelf=indian-literature">indian-literature</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9086236-chaitra?shelf=dysfunctional-family">dysfunctional-family</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9086236-chaitra?shelf=1001-books">1001-books</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9086236-chaitra?shelf=literary-fiction">literary-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer352976164" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12507918548330069412">I&apos;m not sure what it is that put me off this book, but something did. <i>Clear Light of Day</i> is a book about 4 siblings of an moldering Old Delhi family - the 2 boys are important but aren&apos;t given a perspective. The book follows the two girls. The older Bimla, the spinster, who has made it her life&apos;s work to look after a mentally disabled younger brother. She&apos;s also an expert in carrying grudges, and she hasn&apos;t ever forgiven her charismatic older brother for leaving them and going off to marry their</span>
  <span id="freeText12507918548330069412" style="display:none">I'm not sure what it is that put me off this book, but something did. <i>Clear Light of Day</i> is a book about 4 siblings of an moldering Old Delhi family - the 2 boys are important but aren't given a perspective. The book follows the two girls. The older Bimla, the spinster, who has made it her life's work to look after a mentally disabled younger brother. She's also an expert in carrying grudges, and she hasn't ever forgiven her charismatic older brother for leaving them and going off to marry their landlord's daughter. Bimla, who considers herself equal to her brother, who has always been very close, cannot deal with the power imbalance. The younger Tara, who only thought of escaping her family, who loves them still but suffocates in her house, tries hard to make peace between her feuding brother and sister.<br /><br />In a book filled with beautiful description of time and place, of a claustrophobic atmosphere, I found the siblings themselves slightly undefined. I understood their motivations in a way, but it's not because the book confirms it. I don't think of myself as someone who wants everything explained and given to me over a platter, but I thought this book left too many things unexplored, far too many things went unsaid. It not only made me depressed, it also left me dissatisfied. Also, an irrelevant observation, I don't think the book ever uses the phrase <i>clear light of day</i>, but there are several mentions of <i>bright light of day</i>. I wonder why they didn't use the latter?</span>
  <a data-text-id="12507918548330069412" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


