  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_451635975" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/451635975" />
    <a title="Zulu" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13466475-zulu"><img alt="Zulu" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/451635975?book_show_action=true">Nov 08, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Zulu" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Zulu" href="/user/show/13466475-zulu">Zulu</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780140058604" href="/book/show/904290.Clear_Light_of_Day">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer451635975" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5868088308347128170">Trying to read a whole bunch of shorter novels to catch up with my schedule...<br/><br/><em>The Clear Light of Day</em> is about a family in India during and after Independence, but mostly about the two sisters, Bim and Tara, who react to their parents&apos; (benign?) neglect in very different ways, and as a result are rather estranged when they meet again as adults.<br/><br/>The novel was structured in an interesting way, and I&apos;m undecided on whether it worked for me. It begins with Tara coming home to visit Bim at their family</span>
  <span id="freeText5868088308347128170" style="display:none">Trying to read a whole bunch of shorter novels to catch up with my schedule...<br /><br /><em>The Clear Light of Day</em> is about a family in India during and after Independence, but mostly about the two sisters, Bim and Tara, who react to their parents' (benign?) neglect in very different ways, and as a result are rather estranged when they meet again as adults.<br /><br />The novel was structured in an interesting way, and I'm undecided on whether it worked for me. It begins with Tara coming home to visit Bim at their family home in Old Delhi, so that we begin with a sense of their separation, the awkwardness between them, and Tara's impressions of how their home has deteriorated over the years. Then, in two sections, the narrative jumps back to the past, first in Bim's POV and then in Tara's, as they experience the events that led to their separation. In the final section, we come back to the present as they move towards a bit of a reconciliation, although it's incomplete when the novel finishes. I think it's good to establish the problem first, because it's a hook to bring us into the past in part two; but it's also confusing. For instance, Bim and Tara's younger brother Baba is briefly a POV character in the first section, but he's developmentally delayed, and no one spoke about his condition. I thought he might be their father with Alzheimer's at first, until that made no sense, and it wasn't until more than three-quarters of the book had passed that I understood what was going on with him.<br /><br />It's interesting that this book very much felt like Bim's story to me, even though Tara plays just as big a part. I guess it's because it's incumbent on Bim to change her ways, to grow as a person, in order to heal the rift. Tara hasn't changed or grown much since her girlhood--she's very shy, and as an adult she's still dominated by her husband the way she was dominated by her siblings as a child. But Tara has 'escaped' the past, has moved beyond it, physically if not in terms of personal growth. Bim still needs to learn forgiveness, to stop holding grudges, and to reach out to others: to give up the independence she so painfully learned when her parents and aunt all died within a couple of years of one another.<br /><br />The description is rich and lush. There's a child's-eye view of Independence (Bim is 16 in 1949, Tara is 11), which is interesting because you only see sections of it. You <em>can't</em> take it all in, because it's flashes of experience, and children can't have a full understanding. They know their own troubles, and while older brother Raja gets politically involved, he gets involved in an entirely adolescent way: a romantic, poetic, heroic, completely unrealistic involvement that's cut short when he gets TB and has to spend a year in bed.<br /><br />I felt for both Bim and Tara, I was willing to get involved in their POVs and their problems, and what I really enjoyed was that while the story is set in India in and around Independence, it isn't about that. It's about two sisters whose family is distant (and then dead), and whose trouble with money and class and position and needing to get married is what matters. Their relationships with their brothers matters. Their separation with Tara's marriage matters. So, while Independence also matters--the context is important, certainly--Independence is a setting, a circumstance, a life-shaping but not life-determining factor. Because it's a story about two sisters.<br /><br />One of the things I did like about the structure was that with each section, characters gained more sympathy. The girls' aunt is an alcoholic and rather insufferable in Bim's POV because she is constantly having DTs. But in Tara's POV we go further back in time to when their aunt was their primary caregiver who loved them as their parents never did. She becomes a person. The same goes for their brother Baba, who was simply an incumbrance in the first section, but becomes sweet and understandable later on.<br /><br />I kind of hate the parents who are never around, and it's never particularly explained why they're never around, so I wondered about that; but it wasn't really necessary. It didn't detract from the center of the story.<br /><br />All in all this was the kind of book that drew me in so that I was just reading, not thinking about reading. And I like that.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5868088308347128170" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


